# Modelfile for the substack-writer model.
#
# Build:
#   ollama create substack-writer -f Modelfile.substack-writer
# Run:
#   ollama run substack-writer
#
# Swap the FROM tag for whatever your ~32B general model is actually tagged as on
# the Mac Mini host. qwen3:32b is the reference; gemma3:27b is worth A/B-ing for
# warmer prose. This is the draft/critique/revise model — for the stage-6 voice
# polish you can point at a llama3.3:70b build instead.

FROM qwen3:32b

# Prose sampling. ~0.85–0.95 is the professional-writing band: enough variation to
# avoid flat, mechanical output, not so much that it drifts or invents. Below ~0.7
# the prose goes flat and templated. top_p trims the long tail without killing the
# variation temperature is providing.
PARAMETER temperature 0.9
PARAMETER top_p 0.9
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.05

# Context has to hold: craft-principles.md (~2K) + voice.md incl. samples (~1–2K) +
# the author's captured notes (variable) + the working draft (~2–4K) + system. 16K
# is the floor; bump to 32768 if you routinely paste long notes. Cheap on 48GB
# unified memory with a 32B model.
PARAMETER num_ctx 16384

# Thinking suppression via the Modelfile system prompt (the /no_think token), per
# the established pattern — the flag approach SIGABRTs, this doesn't. Keeps drafting
# output clean and fast. If you want the reasoning trace for the critique pass
# specifically, build a second `-think` variant without the /no_think token and
# route stage 4 to it.
SYSTEM """/no_think
You are an editor and ghostwriter for a senior software engineer's professional
portfolio (Substack / technical blog). Your job is craft, not content: you shape the
author's real technical material into tight, credible, well-written prose. You do not
invent facts, benchmarks, quotes, or claims — if a draft needs a specific the author
hasn't supplied, you say so rather than fabricate it. You write in the author's
voice: direct, grounded, first-person, an experienced engineer talking to peers. You
lead with the payoff, name tradeoffs, prove points with concrete specifics, and
strip marketing gloss and LLM-default tics. Short declarative sentences are the
default. You respect the reader's time and you never oversell.
"""
